# <type>(<scope>): <imperative summary, lowercase, ≤72, no period>

What: <what changes technically, ≤100>
Why: <why it is done, ≤100>

# Optional context paragraph, wrapped at ~72
#
# Optional footer:  Tags: <tag>, <tag>   |   Refs: #<issue>   |   BREAKING CHANGE: <descr>
#
# ── Guide ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Types:  feat | fix | docs | refactor | test | perf | build | ci | chore | style | revert
# Scope (one): python|go|rust|docs|spec|conformance|ci|build|repo|cli|core|
#              setup|create|track|remove|sync|publish|doctor|list|config|ssh
# Tags (cross-cutting): breaking | security | performance | ux | migration |
#              dependencies | tech-debt        (soft vocabulary, extensible)
#
# What/Why are REQUIRED for feat/fix/refactor/perf; optional for trivial
# docs/chore/style. What and Why must say different things.
# What: one concise line (~100). Why: no hard cap; if it needs more,
# continue on lines wrapped at ~72 or add a context paragraph.
#
# Do not include AI attribution or secrets/artifacts in the commit.
#
# Example:
#   feat(cli): add global --json envelope with status and reason
#
#   What: every command emits {status, exit_code, message, result, log}.
#   Why: exit codes alone were ambiguous for scripts and CI.
#
#   Refs: #12
